Wash and dry produce. Peel and thinly slice @garlic{1%clove}. Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}, separating whites from greens. Peel and mince @ginger{1%thumb}. Halve @lime{1}. Trim and halve @radishes{3}; thinly slice into half-moons. Roughly chop @cilantro{1/4%ounce}.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tablespoon} in a small #pot{} (medium pot for 4 servings) over medium-high heat. Add garlic and cook, stirring, until fragrant, ~{30%seconds}. Stir in @jasmine rice{3/4%cup}, 1 1/4 cups water (2 1/4 cups for 4), and a pinch of @salt{}. Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce heat to a low simmer. Cook until rice is tender, ~{15-18%minutes}. Keep covered until ready to serve.

While rice cooks, in a small #bowl{}, combine @sweet thai chili sauce{1%ounce}, @ponzu sauce{12%milliliters}, scallion whites, ginger, 1 tsp @cornstarch{1%tablespoon} (2 tsp for 4 servings), and 1 TBSP water (2 TBSP for 4). (Be sure to measure the cornstarch; we sent more.) Stir until cornstarch is dissolved; set aside.

In a medium microwave-safe bowl, combine juice from the lime, 2 TBSP water, @sugar{1/2%teaspoon} (4 TBSP water and 1 tsp sugar for 4), and a pinch of salt. Stir until sugar is dissolved. Add @shredded carrots{4%ounce} and radishes; toss to combine. Cover with #plastic wrap{} and microwave for ~{30-45%seconds}. Set aside to pickle.

Pat @pork chops{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels{}; place between 2 large pieces of #plastic wrap{}. Pound with a #mallet{} or #rolling pin{} until pork is about ¼ inch thick. Season all over with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Heat a large drizzle of oil in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add pork; cook until browned and cooked through, ~{3-5%minutes} per side. Turn off heat; transfer to a #cutting board{} to rest. Wipe out pan and let cool slightly.

Heat same pan over medium heat. Add glaze and ¼ cup water (1/3 cup for 4 servings) and bring to a simmer; cook, stirring occasionally, until slightly reduced, ~{2-3%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper to taste. (If glaze seems too thick, add water 1 tsp at a time.) Turn off heat and stir in @butter{1%tablespoon} (2 TBSP for 4) until melted. Return pork to pan; turn to coat.

Fluff rice with a #fork{}; stir in @butter{1%tablespoon} (2 TBSP for 4 servings) and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Stir in cilantro. Slice pork crosswise.

Divide rice between bowls. Top with pork and pickled veggies (draining first) in separate sections. Drizzle pork with any remaining glaze and garnish with scallion greens. Serve.

> Pork is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.